Geeklaw wrote:I'm not sure how this penchant for candidness and honesty squares with the revelation yesterday that Jobs was willing to engage in abusive patent litigation as a response to employee poaching.It seems to me that the more information that comes to light about his private life the more good and bad that we will see. Hopefully the next generation of creative leaders will learn from both sides of that coin.[edited to expand on the initial thought]I think the honesty here isn't at odds with that particular revelation at all. Jobs "honestly" didn't want Palm poaching Apple employees, and he was "honest" when he said that he would go to great lengths to prevent Palm from doing that. Now, you may find his threat unethical (I'm not really arguing either way), so you might be assuming that contrasts with Jobs' honesty as an "ethical" behavior.But if you look at it more from Jobs' view, Palm was doing something "not cool," so he threatened to retaliate with something that was even more "not cool." That's pretty much classic Jobs right there.
